ROCm decode: evaluate HIP graph capture/replay to reduce launch CPU

Status: Open

Goal
Reduce per-token CPU overhead from repeatedly encoding and launching the same decode graph. Stream batching removes sync barriers, but the CPU still walks metal_graph_encode_token_raw_swa() and launches many HIP kernels every token.

Context
Related: tsk-4, tsk-13, tsk-15. This is distinct from stream-backed command batching: after correctness is restored, capture a stable decode sequence and replay it when shapes/pointers are unchanged. Token id, position, raw-cache row, and small scalar params may need device-side parameter buffers or patched kernel arguments.

Evidence
- ds4.c metal_graph_eval_token_raw_swa() calls metal_graph_encode_token_raw_swa() once per generated token.
- ds4_rocm.c has many hipLaunchKernelGGL sites; decode launch count is high enough to heat CPU cores even when kernels run on GPU.
- HIP graph replay could collapse CPU launch overhead without changing kernel math.

Next steps
1. Measure launch/encode CPU cost with DS4_METAL_GRAPH_TOKEN_PROFILE=1 after tsk-13 is coherent.
2. Prototype HIP graph capture for one-token decode with fixed ctx/raw-cap shape and no debug dumps.
3. Identify dynamic arguments that block replay; move them into device parameter tensors or use HIP graph node parameter updates if stable enough.
4. Compare graph replay vs normal stream batching for generation t/s and CPU utilization.

Validation
- tsk-3 gate passes.
- Same prompt/seed/temp=0 produces identical tokens.
- CPU utilization and per-token encode time decrease without hurting GPU occupancy.